Said it in some videos already, but idk if I laid out my season goals on Instagram yet, so here it is: I plan on picking up where I left off and start the season in (or close to) the top 20. I know the west coast tracks aren’t my strong suit, so if I can be around 20th I’d be extremely happy and that would build a ton of confidence for rounds 4-11 on the east coast. By that time, I want to score points every weekend and work my way down into the top 15 range and put myself in contention for some kind of late-season fill in ride. I really REALLY want to experience life under a semi truck awning at least once in my life, and I feel like there’s no reason I can’t do it this year…and of course get that long-overdue 2 digit number! so those are my goals! Some may see them as unrealistic, but everything I’ve accomplished so far seemed 1000% unrealistic 5 years ago🤷🏼‍♀️ time to believe in myself, work hard, and shoot high! Let’s get it!

I’ve never been a fan of hard-packed dirt (probably because I sucked at it), but I’ve been working extremely hard on changing that this year! I normally treat the hard-pack west coast rounds like warmup races and then find my flow when we come back east, but I think it will be important for me to start this season with some good results to build confidence and achieve the goals I set for myself later in the season. It feels like it’s going well so far!! I’ll let you guys be the judge🤙🏼

Thunder Valley was some huge progress for me! Although the results were similar (26-24), my riding was so much better than the first two rounds. Colorado is an interesting race because it’s close enough to both coasts that you get all the fast Cali boys and all the fast east coast rippers at one race. The factory field might be thinned out, but that’s brought out A TON of fast privateers and I feel like the fast 40 as a whole has never been deeper.

I owe a huge thank you to Tim Bennett and the crew at @tcdracing for helping me find comfort this week. Quite frankly, I was a little lost on setting the new bike up this spring which resulted in me running a 100% bone stock shock (stock components, valving, oil, EVERYTHING) at the first two rounds…after Fox and Hangtown, I knew that stock wasn’t going to cut it and I gave Tim a call. He got to work immediately and got a set in my hands a few days later! Qualifying practice 1 at Thunder was my first time really riding the setting, and the difference became clear after the first bump I hit. It was a learning process all day as I discovered how much faster I could hit sections and not be afraid! Normally my lap times start to drop off around the 20min mark, but my last 3 laps were almost the same as my first 3 which is a great sign and will allow me to push harder earlier in the motos from here on out. It feels great having some confidence back👏🏼

Sorry for the long post, I’m just excited and ready to keep improving at the next few rounds! Highpoint up next. See y’all there🦁💪🏼 📸 @cycledump

This is how the majority of my day was spent at Highpoint. Won’t dwell on it. 2 weeks to work before Redbud @ferrickmoto

Redbud was a good day that had potential to be a massive personal best until an unfortunate shoulder injury…started off 14th in the first qualifier and ended up heading to the gate P-18 which was HUGE for me. I almost always finish better in the races than I do in qualifying, so I was super excited! Got off to a decent start in moto 1 and passed up to 20th before I had a little crash that set me back to 28th. Caught all the way back up to 20th and then had one of the sketchiest moments of my life on the big downhill and felt my shoulder rip funny. This is the same shoulder I dislocated in 2021 and I’ve had some pain ever since, but nothing like this. I was giving it my all and fought super hard all day, so I’m absolutely gutted at the result…I wanted it bad😔

I’ll be checking in with my orthopedic surgeon tomorrow to see how severe it is. Hopefully just some rest and rehab and we can line up in the sand this weekend🤞🏼 I’m finally getting where I want to be, and I’ll be damned if my season ends like this before I accomplish my goals. 

Thank you to @pilot.wealth.advisors and @cpr_mx for jumping on as title sponsors for this weekend! I’ll have another post dedicated to them, but I thought y’all would like to see the awesome @skda.moto kit in the meantime🔥

Thanks for the support everyone. We’ll be back stronger and scoring points asap💪🏼 📸 @mikevizerphoto

Not a post I love to make…😓 Unadilla did a number on my shoulder, so I decided to take Budd’s Creek off and focus on being as healthy as possible for Ironman. After trying to ride today, it’s obvious that my shoulder is in no shape to compete at a professional level. The pain and instability has taken away every scrap of my confidence and I feel like a shell of my former self. Surgery is set for August 30th💉

I would say this is a crap way to end my season, but in all honestly it feels like my season never even started. Just as things started to come together for me at Redbud, this injury halted all progress. Simply put: I’m disgusted and embarrassed with how this summer went and I need to take a long, hard look in the mirror and figure out what changes I need to make in order to never feel this way again. I’m definitely no stranger to failure, but this one stings the worst and quite frankly I’m pissed off. I expect WAY more of myself at this stage in the game. I’ll be back and I’ll be better.

On the bright side, this new @aektivco kit is insanely hot and will be released soon along with a handful of other designs. Keep your eyes peeled🔥

Before and after😬 surgery went well and the shoulder is on the mend! A couple anchor bolts to keep the labrum in place, and a few pleats to tighten things up💪🏼 I honestly thought the pain would be so much worse, but modern surgery has gotten pretty amazing compared to my first operation in 2004. Just so dang excited to not have this slide around anymore while riding. Can’t wait to get back on the machine🤠

Also decided to make a vlog out of the day, so keep an out for that later this afternoon!

2 weeks into recovery and I’m already missing this so much…it makes you realize what you take for granted when you’re in the daily routine of riding, training, bike work, filming, editing, traveling, etc…as odd as it sounds, I think I needed this injury to stoke the flames and give me some new perspective.

Also, thanks to everyone who’s been ordering the signature kit and new merch! It’s always a huge help to the program, but even more so right now with the surgery and not being able to ride/make videos. Still plenty available over at Aektiv.com if you want to support and get some cool gear❤️ @nicktomasunas @aektivco

THE 2 STROKE IS BACK🔥🔥🔥 just got cleared to take my sling off, so it’s time to keep myself occupied with some bike builds until I can ride again. Episode 1 is up on my YouTube channel now. Go have yourself a watch!

6 weeks post-op tomorrow, and I am  absolutely stoked with the recent progress my shoulder has made. The first few weeks were dark, but I can finally see the light at the end of the tunnel (AKA being able to ride again). This has absolutely been the toughest injury I’ve had to rehab from given that the shoulder needs so much strength and range of motion to be stable…I’m putting 100% effort into it right now and it’s making a huge difference. Half way there, let’s go!🤠🤞🏼
Less than 1 month until I’m cleared to ride, so that means a quick trip up to @tcdracing to make sure the 450 is in tip-top shape! Fresh shoulder and some fresh suspension…So dang excited to ride😍
Almost there…probably not a whole lot of slide 3 going on for the first couple of rides✊🏼😝
